{"title_page": "Alfred R\u00f6ssner", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian cross-country skier}}\n'''Alfred \"Fred\" R\u00f6ssner''' (August 16, 1911 &ndash; December 25, 2005) was an [[Austria]]n [[Cross-country skiing|cross-country skier]] who competed in the [[1936 Winter Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[Sankt Johann am Tauern]] and died in [[Salzburg]].\n\nIn 1936 he was a member of the Austrian relay team which finished eighth in the [[Cross-country skiing at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 10 km relay|4x10 km relay competition]]. In the [[Cross-country skiing at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 18 km|18 km event]] he finished 39th.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ro/fred-rossner-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rossner, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian male cross-country skiers]]\n[[Category:Olympic cross-country skiers of Austria]]\n[[Category:Cross-country skiers at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Murtal District]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Styria]]\n\n\n{{Austria-crosscountry-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian cross-country skier}}\n'''Alfred \"Fred\" R\u00f6ssner''' (August 16, 1911 &ndash; December 25, 2005) was an [[Austria]]n [[Cross-country skiing|cross-country skier]] who competed in the [[1936 Winter Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[Sankt Johann am Tauern]] and died in [[Salzburg]].\n\nIn 1936 he was a member of the Austrian relay team which finished eighth in the [[Cross-country skiing at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 10 km relay|4x10 km relay competition]]. In the [[Cross-country skiing at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's 18 km|18 km event]] he finished 39th.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ro/fred-rossner-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rossner, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian male cross-country skiers]]\n[[Category:Olympic cross-country skiers of Austria]]\n[[Category:Cross-country skiers at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Murtal District]]\n\n{{Austria-crosscountry-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Severo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddingCategory:Sportspeople from Styria", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_R%C3%B6ssner"}
{"title_page": "Time, Love and Tenderness (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1991 single by Michael Bolton}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Time, Love and Tenderness\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Michael Bolton]]\n| album      = [[Time, Love & Tenderness]]\n| released   = 1991\n| format     = [[Single (music)#7-inch format|7\" vinyl]], [[12-inch single|12\" vinyl]], [[CD single]], [[cassette single]], [[maxi single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 5:31\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Diane Warren]]\n| producer   = [[Walter Afanasieff]], Michael Bolton\n| prev_title = [[Love Is a Wonderful Thing (Michael Bolton song)|Love Is a Wonderful Thing]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[When a Man Loves a Woman (song)|When a Man Loves a Woman]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n\n'''\"Time, Love and Tenderness\"''' is a song written by [[Diane Warren]] and performed by [[Michael Bolton]]. Released as a [[single (music)|single]] from his [[Time, Love & Tenderness|album of the same title]], the song reached number seven on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, becoming Bolton's fifth top-ten single in the United States. It was also the singer's fourth song to top the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]] chart. Worldwide the song reached number four in Canada, number 27 in Sweden and number 28 in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Personnel==\n*Michael Bolton - vocals\n*[[Walter Afanasieff]] - synthesized bass, keyboards, synthesizers, drums, percussion\n*[[Michael Landau]] - electric guitar\n* Gary Cirimelli - [[Synclavier]] programming\n* [[Ren Klyce]] - [[Akai AX60]] and [[Fairlight CMI]] programming\n* Greg \"Gigi\" Gonaway - timbales\n* Kitty Beethoven, Larry Batiste, Sandy Griffith, Chris Hawkins, Jeanie Tracy, Michael Bolton - backing vocals\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable 